# 1. Current regulations on short-term rentals in San Francisco are somewhat accountable; however, they fail to provide sufficient accountability. Hosts must register their property with the city, and it is expected that Airbnb will record a policy number as part of its listings. Enforcement relies heavily on third parties using web scraping methods to identify violations. As such, there are inherent inconsistencies where many violations will go unidentified and very few acts of proactivity will be taken by either the platform or the city relative to enforcement. Furthermore, hosts can incorrectly report and/or fail to report certain information, and platforms could potentially be unable to verify compliance. To foster better accountability, Airbnb's registration numbers should be directly verified with the city's database before the listed property can go live on its platform. This will help place the responsibility on the platform as opposed to relying on outside actors. From a Software Engineering Code of Ethics perspective, prioritizing public good over all other considerations aligns directly with ensuring a system's ability to design against causing harm versus reacting to it after-the-fact.

# 2. One major consideration regarding the legality of web scraping has to do with the availability of data; whether the data being accessed is "public", meaning that no restrictions or authentication are necessary to gain access, or whether the data is subject to some sort of restriction/authentication measures. The CFAA has been interpreted to provide a basis for arguing that accessing data without permission may be considered illegal, even if that data is publicly available. Thus, it creates an uncertainty for what constitutes 'unauthorised access' because, in many circumstances, the definition of 'unauthorised access' is not clearly provided for within the CFAA. I feel this distinction is important because, when accessing public data for ‘research’ or ‘accountability’ purposes, this should be considered different from accessing restricted data by circumventing security measures. And, with no clear boundaries on how to operate within the CFAA, many developers may unknowingly violate the law while attempting to operate in good faith.

# 3. The most appropriate way to approach web scraping is first to not collect people's private/identifying/sensitive data, no matter if that data is available publicly; just because something can be accessed does not equate to being usable without considering the potential risks involved. Secondly, web scrapers should always have transparency to what's being collected and why there exists a benefit for the community or intent of producing accurate information. For example, web scraping done to find out about violations of regulations or to help improve services offered by government entities is much better than scraping web content for the sole purpose of making money off of users' information. By having these guidelines in place, web scraping will be done ethically as it relates with overall ethical principles for all technology.